      "@id": "https://example.org/risk-record/USFED/Individual_Assistance_(IA)_&_Public_Assistance_(PA)_Projections",
      "@type": "vair:RiskRecord",
      "source": "USFED",
      "dct:identifier": "Individual Assistance (IA) & Public Assistance (PA) Projections",
      "title": "Individual Assistance (IA) & Public Assistance (PA) Projections",
      "description": "The purpose of these supervised learning models is two-fold:\n\n1.\tFor informational purposes: the models will produce predictions for to-be-determined quantities of interest. These quantities are often of interest to Agency personnel in the field, region, and headquarters, as well as DHS, OMB, NSC, and the Whitehouse.\n2.\tFor decisional purposes: in addition to being informative, the models predictions are likely to be used for decision making. This may include implicit use (e.g., seeing that there are a large number of households that require assistance may motivate FEMA CFO to consider requesting additional funding for the Disaster Relief Fund) or explicit use (e.g., the number of estimated housing units required may be used to determine the number of housing units to order just-in-time).\n\nAnticipated benefits of using supervised learning models include:\n1.\tIncreased predictive performance: supervised learning models offer means of quantifying and choosing models with the best possible predictive performance.\n2.\tTimely prediction: supervised learning models can produce reasonably high performance predictions based on limited data.\n3.\tQuantification of uncertainty: supervised learning models are able to provide prediction intervals and predictive distributions in addition to point predictions to give users a sense of how uncertainty is inherent in the prediction.\n4.\tRigor: supervised learning models are well founded on statistical learning theory and provide a level of mathematical rigor that speaks to the reliability and limitations of methods. These supervised learning models produce predictions, not recommendations and not decisions (though they can be used to inform human users in making recommendations and decisions).\n\nAt minimum, these supervised learning models will produce point predictions for the different quantities of interest for disaster declarations. Additionally supervised learning models may produce prediction intervals or predictive distributions as feasible and appropriate for the given prediction problem. Often these outputs will be shared via business intelligence tools (e.g., Tableau or PowerBI) for wide internal FEMA use. Some predictions may be shared to a more restricted audience through simpler means (e.g., an excel workbook) as appropriate.",
      "annexDomain": "https://w3id.org/vair#EssentialPublicServices",
      "actorRole": "https://w3id.org/dpv#AIDeployer",
      "systemPattern": "https://w3id.org/vair#UnspecifiedPattern",
      "rights": [
        "https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/rights#A34-SocialSecurity",
        "https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/rights#A8-ProtectionOfPersonalData"
      ],
      "harms": [
        "https://w3id.org/dpv/risk#Harm"
      ],
      "notes": "Auto annotation v0.4 rule-based"
    },
